Exploring indicators of economic development


We will be using an open dataset from Kaggle. It is The World Development Indicators dataset obtained from the World Bank containing over a thousand annual indicators of economic development from hundreds of countries around the world.

This is a slightly modified version of the original dataset from The World Bank

Preparation¶

In this section we import the necessary libraries and data that we will require for this project.

Data cleaning¶

It's evident from the data preview above that a lot of information seems to be jumbled together. We would prefer to have some better organized data that fits the purpose of this project. Therefore, we perform some data cleaning.

In this section we create seperate tables for countries, regions and income groups because these are the categories we shall be exlporing. We also remove columns that may not be required at the moment and take care of missing values if any.

In [4]:
#Data Cleaning

#Remove features that won't be used
del indicators['CountryCode']
del indicators['IndicatorCode']

#Create filter masks to extract income group specific data from indicators table
income_group_mask1 = indicators['CountryName'].str.contains('income')
income_group_mask2 = indicators['CountryName'].str.contains('levels')

#Update the income groups table with income group specific data
income_groups = indicators[income_group_mask1 & ~income_group_mask2]
income_groups.rename(columns={'CountryName':'IncomeGroup'}, inplace=True)

#Get the countries with missing values for region
regions_na = np.setdiff1d(regions['ShortName'].tolist(), regions.dropna()['ShortName'].tolist())
regions_na = np.setdiff1d(regions_na, income_groups['IncomeGroup'].tolist())

#Create filter masks to extract region specific data from indicators table
region_mask1 = indicators['CountryName'].isin(regions['Region'].tolist())
region_mask2 = indicators['CountryName'].isin(regions_na)
region_mask3 = np.logical_or(region_mask1, region_mask2)

#Update the regions table with region specific data
regions = indicators[region_mask3]
regions.rename(columns={'CountryName':'Region'}, inplace=True)

#Create filter masks to extract country specific data from indicators table
indicator_mask1 = indicators['CountryName'].isin(regions['Region'].tolist())
indicator_mask2 = indicators['CountryName'].isin(income_groups['IncomeGroup'].tolist())

#Update countries table with country specific data
countries = indicators[~indicator_mask1 & ~indicator_mask2]

Section A: Exploring the relationship between carbon emissions per capita and life expectancy at birth across the world


In this section, we explore world aggregate data for carbon emissions and life expectancy at birth.

We look at trends to get a sense of how these indicators have changed over time, color maps, scatter plots and other visualizations to understand their perfomance and the relationships between these indicators.

1. Carbon emissions per capita¶

Carbon emissions per capita are measured as the total amount of carbon dioxide emitted by a country as a consequence of all relevant human (production and consumption) activities, divided by the population of the country. In this sub-section, we explore the performance of the indicator across the world.

In [9]:

world_co2 = regions[co2_mask1 & co2_mask2]

Graph notes:

  • Life expectancy, for both males and females, has increased steadly over time
  • Females seem to always have a higher life expectancy than males

We may also intuitively note that the life expectancy of males and females seem to have a strong relationship. We examine this by looking at correlation.

In [26]:
#Determine the correlation of the indicators
np.corrcoef(world_leb_male['Value'], world_leb_female['Value'])
Out[26]:
array([[1.        , 0.99901626],
       [0.99901626, 1.        ]])

0.999 is a nearly perfect positive correlation (the highest being 1). That's a very strong relationship. A high positive correlation means that the two features will increase/decrease in parallel to a greater extent. It is important to note however that this does not infer causation.

3. Relationship between carbon emissions per capita and life expectancy at birth¶

In this sub-section, we explore the nature of the relationship that exists between the two indicators.

3.1 CO2 emissions & life expectancy (males)¶

In [27]:
#Check to see if the range of records is equal

print()
print("CO2 emission data: ", min(world_co2['Year']), ' to ', max(world_co2['Year']))
print()
print("Life expectancy data: ", min(world_leb_male['Year']), ' to ', max(world_leb_female['Year']))

CO2 emission data:  1960  to  2011

Life expectancy data:  1960  to  2013

Life expectancy records seem to be greater by 2, let's fix that

In [28]:
#Data cleaning

world_leb_male = world_leb_male[world_leb_male['Year'] <= 2011]
In [29]:
#Check the correlation of the indicators

np.corrcoef(world_leb_male['Value'], world_co2['Value'])
Out[29]:
array([[1.        , 0.84872372],
       [0.84872372, 1.        ]])

0.8487 is a very high positive correlation indicating that there is a strong linear relationship between the two features. Again, we cannot infer from the correlation value alone whether this relationship is causal or not.

Let's think about these results for a minute however. We would have expected, for obvious reasons, that as carbon emissions go up, life expectancy goes down (a negative correlation). However, we are observing the opposite. This could be because the longer people live (life expectancy goes up), the more carbon they will emit (carbon emission per capita goes up) or the relationship might not be causal at all.

Further investigation and expert domain knowledge might be required to comprehensively understand the nature of this relationship.

3.2 CO2 emissions & life expectancy (females)¶

Now, we might have intuitively guessed the results for life expectancy of females.

Given we know that life expectancy of females has a high positive correlation with life expectancy of males, and that life expectancy of males has a high positive correlation with CO2 emissions per capita, we might assume that life expectancy of females has a high positive correlation with CO2 emissions per capita.

However, it is important to note that correlation is not necessarily transitive. So let's explore this and see what comes up.

In [30]:
#Data cleaning
world_leb_female = world_leb_female[world_leb_female['Year'] <= 2011]

#Check the correlation of the indicators
np.corrcoef(world_leb_female['Value'], world_co2['Value'])
Out[30]:
array([[1.       , 0.8446923],
       [0.8446923, 1.       ]])

Section B: Exploring hospital beds (per 1000 people) across income groups


In this section, we explore income group specific data for the hospital beds (per 1000 people) indicator. We look at trends over time to see how the indicator performs across income groups.

The indicator is a hospital bed to population ratio. The World Health Organization's recommended standard is 5 beds per 1,000 population

In [32]:
#Extract income groups
groups = income_groups['IncomeGroup'].unique().tolist()

Income group definitions:¶

  • High-income economies are those in which 2014 GNI per capita was USD 12,736 or more
  • Upper-middle-income economies are those in which 2014 GNI per capita was between USD 4,126 and USD 12,735
  • Middle-income economies are those in which 2014 GNI per capita was between USD 1,046 and USD 12,735
  • Lower-middle-income economies are those in which 2014 GNI per capita was between USD 1,046 and USD 4,125
  • Low-income economies are those in which 2014 GNI per capita was USD 1,045 or less

Graph notes:¶

  • Data for Low-income economies is only available up to 1990
  • Data for Middle-income and Upper-middle-income economies is only available from 1970
  • High-income economies seem to have a significantly higher hospital beds to population ratio, although it has dropped over the years
  • Other economies still stagger below the WHO's recommended standard



Section C: Exploring age dependency ratio across regions


In this section, we explore region specific data for the age dependency ratio indicator. We look at how the indicator performed across different regions in the year 2014.

The dependency ratio is an age-population ratio of those typically not in the labor force and those typically in the labor force. It is used to measure the pressure on the productive population.

A high dependency ratio means those of working age, and the overall economy, face a greater burden in supporting the aging population. The global average was 54.36 as of 2018.

In [34]:
#Create filter masks to extract dependecy ratios for the regions
mask1 = regions['IndicatorName'].str.contains('Age dependency ratio \(')
mask2 = regions['Year'].isin([2014])
mask3 = regions['Region'].str.contains('developing only')
dependency = regions[mask1 & mask2 & ~mask3]
del dependency['IndicatorName']
del dependency['Year']

#View some sections of the dependency data
